Introduction and Research Questions:

Covid-19 has been a global health crisis since late 2019, and here we would like to focus on covid-19 cases and deaths in the five regions in New York City. We will address several questions and give a conclusion of what causes the increase in cases and deaths.

  • Which of the five regions has the highest death in covid-19? We will analyze which of the five regions has the highest death in covid-19 and maybe give assumption or inference of why this region has the highest death.

  • On which day has the most COVID-19 cases? We will explore and find out which day has the most covid-19 cases.

  • Which month in each year had the most cases in NYC? Most deaths? We will give numeric values showing which month in each year has the most cases and deaths in NYC and explain why it has the most cases and deaths.

  • What is the average number of deaths and COVID-19 cases on a yearly, monthly basis in NYC? We will calculate the average number of deaths and cases for each year and each month and see if there are any increases or decreases due to the vaccines.

  • Visualization of NYC COVID-19 cases and deaths breakdown by year, month, day, and weekday. We will create plots to easily compare which month and year has the highest or lowest cases and deaths.

Description of your data set:

This data set counts the daily number of New York City residents who tested positive for COVID-19, were hospitalized with COVID-19, and the number of deaths among COVID-19 patients. This data set includes 67 variables and 1158 observations. These observations are recorded from 2/29/2020 to 5/1/2023. All of the variables are integer values. For the first few columns, it counts the daily number of cases and deaths in New York City, then counts the average seven days of those records. After that, it broke down into five different regions, which are Brooklyn (BK), Bronx (BX), Manhattan (MN), Queens (QU), and Staten Island (SI). Each region also counts the total cases and deaths and the average seven days of those cases.

Methods

We mostly used the tydiverse package for our data exploration to get our results. For example, we used lubridate to change the format of the date, we also used ggplot2 to do our visualization for our research questions.

Data Exploration

We figured out that there are 1158 total days that were considered in the data set with a total of 38,777 deaths and 2,731,350 cases. We aslo figured out that the total death rate based on the total cases for 2020 was larger followed by year 2023.

##   TotalDays TotalDeaths TotalCases
## 1      1158       38777    2731350

Total Deaths by Region

Which of the five regions has the highest total death count of COVID-19? - According to the data from 2020 to 2023, Brooklyn had the highest number of deaths related to COVID-19 with a total of 12,107. Queens followed with 11,605 deaths, then the Bronx with 7,290 deaths, Manhattan with 5,311 deaths, and finally Staten Island with 2,462 deaths. The order of these regions coincides with their population, which explains the differences in their death counts. In order from largest to smallest population, the regions are: Brooklyn, Queens, Bronx, Manhattan, and Staten Island.

##   SI_DEATH QN_DEATH MN_DEATH BK_DEATH BX_DEATH
## 1     2462    11605     5311    12107     7290

Graphical Display of deaths and cases of COVID-19 per Month and Year

We can see from the bar graph for total cases per month that there was a spike in cases during December 2021 and January 2022. The reason behind this has to do to people starting to lose fear of getting infected. They started to celebrate the holidays. Due to New York being a popular tourist attraction for the holidays, more people visited and got together to celebrate. Also, we noticed that there is a pattern in cases and deaths in which the beginning and end of each year have more cases than in between. This also has to do to people celebrating the holidays. Lastly, once again we can see that the is a spike in April 2020, which has to do with the fact that it was when COVID started to spread. We were not prepared to know how it would affect us and how we needed to get protected, which made the affects worse.

Which month in each year had the most cases in NYC?

  • We explored data on the months with the highest number of COVID-19 cases from 2020 to 2023. In 2020, April had the most cases with a total of 109,296. This can be attributed to the early stages of the pandemic when testing sites were being established nationwide. The month with the highest number of cases in 2021 was December, with a total of 506,398. For 2022, January had 460,364 cases, and January 2023 had 57,597 cases. It’s evident that the months with the most cases are either early or late in the year.

Most deaths?

  • We have analyzed data on the month in each of the years 2020, 2021, 2022, and 2023, that had the highest number of deaths. In April 2020, the month with the most cases, there were 12,716 deaths. February 2021 had a total of 2,093 deaths, while January 2022 saw 3,001 deaths. Finally, January 2023 had a total of 626 deaths. It is clear from this data that the months with the highest number of deaths are in the early part of the year.

  • As a result of COVID containment measures, vaccine development, and research, there was a significant decrease in the number of COVID cases and deaths in January 2023 compared to April 2020.

Conclusion:

From the graphs we can see that normally there are more cases towards the beginning and end of the year, which might be cased by several factors such as national holidays or family reunion. Overall we noticed that the amount of total deaths started to decrease over time, which might be due to people being more careful such as quarantine and getting the shot. As for total cases, they started to increase, which might be due to more and more people getting tested.
